snippet.textDisplay:
BMW is facing a severe mid-life crisis - It has done very well in terms of its ICE drive trains but is now facing an uncertain future with the advent of EVs. In short, it is torn between sticking to the comfort of past success and facing eventual obsolescence or abandoning ICE altogether and innovating its way into EVs (which ironically will hasten the death of her ICE vehicle market).


Its the same with many now defunct companies such as Kodak which had great success with old photographic systems and inertia when moving to the emerging technology of camera phones. The same happened with Olivetti which tried unsuccessfully to pivot from producing typewriters (google it if you do not know what this is) into computer keyboards and peripherals.


Technological obsolescence is a hard nut to crack in every industry. It is especially difficult when you have a storied past with all your historical baggage and a massive re-tooling / re-skilling effort to balance existing cash cows with very uncertain payoffs.with some new-fangled technologies.


BMW would also probably have no need for like 80% of her workforce if they do move full-on into EVs because the electric motor is a completely different animal and is much simpler compared to ICE engines in terms of function and maintenance.
